# === !name : I-type encoding =======================================
# Used by ADDI/JALR: lo12 displacement signed; the +4 adjustment
# accounts for AUIPC->ADDI being a 2-instruction pair where the
# second instruction is at PC+4 relative to the AUIPC. lo12 << 20
# maps to bits 20-31 of the 32-bit instruction word.
13 01 01 FF
23 30 11 00
EF F0 DF DD                                      # call store_pointer
33 0E A5 41                                      # t3 = target - IP (displacement)
13 0E 4E 00                                      # t3 = disp + 4 (AUIPC+ADDI pair)
13 1E 4E 03                                      # isolate low 12 bits
13 5E 4E 03                                      # zero-extend lo12
13 1E 4E 01                                      # t3 = lo12 << 20 (I-type XOR)
B3 C4 C4 01                                      # s1 ^= encoded
83 30 01 00
13 01 01 01
6F F0 1F D0                                      # →sp
# === @name : B-type encoding =======================================
# RISC-V B-type instruction encoding scrambles the displacement
# bits across multiple non-contiguous fields:
#   bit 12 of disp -> bit 31 of instr
#   bits 11..5     -> bits 25..30
#   bits 4..1      -> bits 8..11
#   bit 12 (sign)  -> bit 7 (overlap with bit 11)
# The code below extracts each field with shifts/AND and ORs them
# into the accumulator t4 a piece at a time.
13 01 01 FF
23 30 11 00
EF F0 DF DA                                      # call store_pointer
33 0E A5 41                                      # t3 = displacement
93 0E 00 00                                      # accumulator
37 1F 00 00                                      # t5 = 0x1000
33 7F EE 01                                      # bit 12
13 1F 3F 01                                      # -> bit 31
B3 EE EE 01
13 5F 5E 00
13 7F FF 03
13 1F 9F 01
B3 EE EE 01
13 5F 1E 00
13 7F FF 00
13 1F 8F 00
B3 EE EE 01
13 5F BE 00
13 7F 1F 00
13 1F 7F 00
B3 EE EE 01
B3 C4 D4 01                                      # s1 ^= B-type encoded
83 30 01 00
13 01 01 01
6F F0 DF C9                                      # →sp
# === $name : J-type encoding =======================================
# JAL displacement is also scrambled:
#   bit 20 (sign) -> bit 31 of instr
#   bits 10..1    -> bits 21..30
#   bit 11        -> bit 20
#   bits 19..12   -> bits 12..19  (these stay at the low end)
# Mostly the same pattern as B-type but with a different bit map.
13 01 01 FF
23 30 11 00
EF F0 9F D4                                      # call store_pointer
33 0E A5 41                                      # t3 = displacement
93 0E 00 00                                      # accumulator
37 0F 10 00                                      # t5 = 0x100000
33 7F EE 01                                      # bit 20
13 1F BF 00                                      # -> bit 31
B3 EE EE 01
13 5F 1E 00
13 7F FF 3F
13 1F 5F 01
B3 EE EE 01
13 5F BE 00
13 7F 1F 00
13 1F 4F 01
B3 EE EE 01
13 5F CE 00
13 7F FF 0F
13 1F CF 00
B3 EE EE 01
B3 C4 D4 01                                      # s1 ^= J-type encoded
83 30 01 00
13 01 01 01
6F F0 9F C3                                      # →sp
# === .name : 4-byte little-endian raw value ========================
# `.name` reads 8 hex digits and emits them as a 4-byte LE word
# (used by data tables in the linker scripts: vtables,
# constant pools, etc.). Each hex pair builds one byte; the
# four bytes are accumulated low-to-high into a 32-bit word.
13 01 01 FE
23 30 11 00
23 34 01 00                                      # accumulator = 0
EF 00 40 24                                      # call fgetc
EF 00 C0 0C                                      # call hex
23 3C A1 00                                      # save high nibble
EF 00 80 23                                      # call fgetc
EF 00 00 0C                                      # call hex
03 3E 81 01
13 1E 4E 00
33 65 AE 00                                      # byte
03 3E 81 00                                      # accum
33 6E AE 00
23 34 C1 01
EF 00 80 21                                      # call fgetc
EF 00 00 0A                                      # call hex
23 3C A1 00                                      # save high nibble
EF 00 C0 20                                      # call fgetc
EF 00 40 09                                      # call hex
03 3E 81 01
13 1E 4E 00
33 65 AE 00                                      # byte
13 15 85 00                                      # byte << 8
03 3E 81 00                                      # accum
33 6E AE 00
23 34 C1 01
EF 00 80 1E                                      # call fgetc
EF 00 00 07                                      # call hex
23 3C A1 00                                      # save high nibble
EF 00 C0 1D                                      # call fgetc
EF 00 40 06                                      # call hex
03 3E 81 01
13 1E 4E 00
33 65 AE 00                                      # byte
13 15 05 01                                      # byte << 16
03 3E 81 00                                      # accum
33 6E AE 00
23 34 C1 01
EF 00 80 1B                                      # call fgetc
EF 00 00 04                                      # call hex
23 3C A1 00                                      # save high nibble
EF 00 C0 1A                                      # call fgetc
EF 00 40 03                                      # call hex
03 3E 81 01
13 1E 4E 00
33 65 AE 00                                      # byte
13 15 85 01                                      # byte << 24
03 3E 81 00                                      # accum
33 6E AE 00
23 34 C1 01
03 3E 81 00                                      # final accumulator
B3 C4 C4 01                                      # s1 ^= dot value
83 30 01 00
13 01 01 02
6F F0 DF B5                                      # →sp
